code_changes.content:
{
  "buggy_files": [
    "sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c"
  ],
  "buggy_functions": [
    "azx_resume",
    "azx_runtime_resume",
    "azx_rirb_get_response",
    "azx_init_chip"
  ],
  "confidence": 0.95,
  "reasoning": "The bug occurs because when HDA codec communication times out before suspend, the timeout handler in azx_rirb_get_response sets degraded state flags (chip->polling_mode = 1, chip->single_cmd = 1, chip->poll_count incremented). These flags are never reset during suspend/resume. During resume, azx_resume/azx_runtime_resume call azx_init_chip(chip, 1), but azx_init_chip skips CORB/RIRB reinitialization when chip->single_cmd is 1 (line 1222-1223: 'if (!chip->single_cmd) azx_init_cmd_io(chip)'). Additionally, azx_reset only enables unsolicited responses if chip->single_cmd is 0 (lines 1105-1107). As a result, the controller remains in degraded single-command mode after resume, causing codec communication failures, timeouts, and choppy audio output. The fix requires resetting chip->polling_mode = 0, chip->single_cmd = single_cmd (module parameter), and chip->poll_count = 0 before reinitializing the chip on resume."
}

